reviewText: Katy opens her backstage dressing room, her wardrobe and her heart for the cameras. It mostly focuses on behind the scenes of the Hello Katy year-long world tour, as she works her little strawberry flavoured socks off touring the world. If you've never heard of her, (really?) this is a good place to start.

Unofficial and very clearly so...you can tell how unofficial this is by the lack of production values and poor excuses for detailed or even accurate info on the singer Katy Perry's career and life. Hardly any exclusive or even remotely interesting footage of Katy herself and you've all heard and seen this before.
Katy is a one of a kind performer, and this video proves it.

This is essentially a TV show moved to video. If you're interested in learning about Katy Perry's personal life, this show will give you more details on her family life & history with a little less spin & glitz than "Part of Me" but -- somewhat ironically -- it seems *less* intimate than that film because so much of "Katy Perry: Getting Intimate" involves watching other people talk about her.

Intimate backstage pass. Answers the eternal, burning question: How does one go about asking Katy out. The answer: Very carefully and "it's a small pond," guys. {she's mine.}

I was expecting something of the caliber of Taylor Swift's "Journey To Fearless." Stories and songs mixed in together. Some heart and honesty moments. Not close.

While the production value (camera, editing, sound, etc) of the program kept me awake and attentive most of the time, the content did not. No musical performance by Perry, a handful of entertainment talking-head groupies praising everything about the artist, and no depth/insight from the material, or the artist's own statements. I watched the show with the intention of being sold on why I should download some of her music, like I did right after watching Swift's "Fearless."

The only interesting news here, although limited, was finding out that she supposedly writes her own material. That part earns the two stars. The rest you could discover on the Entertainment shows "every weeknight at 6:30!" No "getting intimate" required.
